<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="frontend-design">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>dev</group>
    <domain>frontend-developer</domain>
    <summary>Four-phase workflow for UI exploration: capture requirements, brainstorm 3–5 distinct variants with working code, select and refine, build Storybook and components.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>design</tag>
      <tag>variant-exploration</tag>
      <tag>ui-design</tag>
      <tag>brainstorming</tag>
      <tag>storybook</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Frontend Design Variant Exploration</title>

    <summary>A four-phase workflow for UI surfaces where multiple visual directions are explored before committing: (1) capture requirements (type, style, tech), (2) brainstorm 3–5 distinct variants via agent into designs/variant-N-slug/, each with working code and a rationale, (3) user selects and refines, (4) Storybook agent builds stories and component agent finalizes typed components. Variants must differ in typeface, density, color, and motion — not just palette.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>LLMs given a single "design this" prompt converge on one SaaS-average aesthetic. Structured divergence forces 3–5 meaningfully distinct directions, accelerates human decision-making, and persists design rationale so future agents know why a direction was chosen. The 3–5-variant ceiling prevents decision paralysis; more than 5 options reliably delays or prevents selection.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Starting a new UI surface (landing, dashboard, form, component set) with no visual decisions yet.</item>
        <item>Solo dev or small team wanting LLM-driven design exploration before implementation.</item>
        <item>Requirements exist but visual direction does not; brainstorming variants accelerates kickoff.</item>
        <item>Storybook is the deliverable — each variant must be explorable in isolation.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Existing product with a mature design system — converging is more important than diverging.</item>
        <item>One-off internal tool where any reasonable UI suffices.</item>
        <item>Marketing pages where copy and photography drive design more than component patterns.</item>
        <item>Strict brand guideline enforcement: variant exploration generates ineligible options.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="variant-diversity-constraints">
      <p>Each brainstormed variant must differ from all others in at least three dimensions to force meaningful divergence and surface unexpected solutions.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Each brainstormed variant must differ from all others in at least three of: typeface, color palette family, density (tight vs airy), and motion style. Variants that share two of these are considered duplicates and must be regenerated.</statement>
        <rationale>LLMs default to one "safe SaaS aesthetic" copied 3–5 times. Explicit diversity constraints force meaningfully distinct directions that accelerate human selection and surface unexpected solutions.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="three-to-five-variant-ceiling">
      <p>The ceiling is both a UX constraint and a decision-making principle. More than 5 options reliably delays or prevents selection.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Generate exactly 3 to 5 design variants. Never fewer (too little divergence), never more (decision paralysis above 5). The ceiling is a UX constraint, not a budget constraint.</statement>
        <rationale>Research on choice overload shows that more than 5 options reliably delays or prevents selection. The 3–5 range is the minimum for meaningful divergence and the maximum for actionable choice.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="token-persistence">
      <p>Keep variant-local tokens isolated until selection is final. Premature global updates contaminate the project before a direction is chosen.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Persist each variant's tokens (color, type scale, spacing) in a local designs/variant-N-slug/tokens.css. Promote tokens to the global tailwind.config or globals.css only after the user selects a variant.</statement>
        <rationale>Premature global token updates contaminate the project before a direction is chosen. Variant-local tokens isolate each option and make the promotion step an explicit, reviewable commit.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="a11y-gate-per-variant">
      <p>Accessibility failures discovered after selection require a redesign loop. Running axe per variant in brainstorm eliminates ineligible options early.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Run axe-core (or equivalent) on every variant during the brainstorm phase, before presenting to the user. Never surface a variant with WCAG AA failures.</statement>
        <rationale>a11y failures discovered after selection require a redesign loop. Running axe per variant in brainstorm eliminates ineligible options early and avoids sunk-cost redesigns.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="rationale-requirement">
      <p>Design without rationale becomes orphaned context in 6 months. Future agents need the rationale to extend the design consistently.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Each variant's README must include: audience fit, aesthetic levers used (the explicit diversity constraints applied), and trade-offs. A variant without rationale is rejected.</statement>
        <rationale>Design without rationale becomes orphaned context in 6 months. Future agents given the rationale can extend the design consistently; without it they guess.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="runnable-variants">
      <p>Reviewers must be able to click and interact with variants, not read source code. Non-runnable variants prevent accurate evaluation.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Each variant must be runnable as static HTML or a Storybook story. Reviewers must be able to click and interact, not read code. Non-runnable variants are invalid deliverables.</statement>
        <rationale>Reviewers cannot evaluate typography, spacing, and motion from source code alone. Interactive variants prevent "looks great in code, terrible in browser" selection errors.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="phase-1-requirements-capture">
      <p>Before dispatching any subagent, collect the four essential inputs. Brainstorming without these produces the average SaaS aesthetic.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Before dispatching any subagent, collect: surface type (landing | dashboard | form | component set), style direction (minimalist | bold | corporate | playful), tech stack, and brand constraints. Do not brainstorm without these four inputs.</statement>
        <rationale>Brainstorming without a style direction produces the average SaaS aesthetic. Explicit inputs become the diversity constraints that force genuinely distinct variants.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Canonical requirements capture">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
requirements = AskUserQuestion([
    {"question": "Surface type?", "options": ["landing", "dashboard", "form", "component-set"]},
    {"question": "Style direction?", "options": ["minimalist", "bold", "corporate", "playful", "editorial"]},
    {"question": "Tech stack?", "options": ["React+TS", "Next.js", "Vue", "HTML/CSS"]},
    {"question": "Brand constraints?", "placeholder": "colors, fonts, logo, or 'none'"},
])
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="phase-2-brainstorm-dispatch">
      <p>Dispatch the brainstorm agent with explicit diversity constraints derived from requirements. Each variant goes into a separate directory with complete working code.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Dispatch faion-frontend-brainstormer-agent with explicit diversity constraints derived from requirements. Each variant goes into designs/variant-N-slug/. The prompt must forbid shared typeface, palette family, or density across variants.</statement>
        <rationale>Without explicit constraints, LLMs generate one canonical design repeated 3–5 times with minor color shifts. The constraint prohibitions force meaningful divergence.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Brainstorm dispatch with diversity constraints">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
Task(
    subagent_type="faion-frontend-brainstormer-agent",
    prompt=f"""Create exactly 3-5 DISTINCT design variants for: {requirements.surface_type}
Tech: {requirements.tech}. Style anchor: {requirements.style}.

DIVERSITY CONSTRAINTS (enforce all):
- Each variant must use a different typeface pairing
- No two variants may share the same color palette family
- Density must vary: at least one tight, one airy
- Motion: vary from zero to expressive

Each variant must deliver:
1. Working code under designs/variant-{{N}}-{{slug}}/
2. tokens.css with variant-local tokens (do NOT update globals)
3. README.md with: audience fit, aesthetic levers, trade-offs
4. Runnable as static HTML or Storybook story
5. axe-core pass before submission

Comparison table at the end contrasting all variants on: typeface, palette, density, motion."""
)
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="phase-3-selection-and-refinement">
      <p>Present variants to the user with comparison. During refinement, pass only the chosen variant's files to avoid token budget exhaustion and regression toward rejected options.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Present variants to the user with the comparison table. After selection, dispatch a refinement subagent with only the chosen variant's files — never the full brainstorm context. Re-quote the original spec at every refinement iteration.</statement>
        <rationale>Passing full brainstorm context into refinement exhausts token budget and causes the agent to regress toward rejected variants. Context isolation keeps refinement focused.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Refinement with isolated context">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
# After user selects variant N
chosen_dir = f"designs/variant-{N}-{slug}"
Task(
    subagent_type="faion-frontend-brainstormer-agent",
    prompt=f"""Refine {chosen_dir} based on feedback: {user_feedback}

Original spec: {requirements}
Constraint: only edit files inside {chosen_dir}.
Do NOT modify globals.css or tailwind.config yet.
Deliver updated runnable preview + diff vs previous iteration."""
)
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="phase-4-token-promotion-and-storybook">
      <p>After final approval, promote tokens in a dedicated commit, then dispatch Storybook and component agents in sequence. Never merge these into one commit.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>After final approval, promote the chosen variant's tokens.css to globals.css or tailwind.config in a dedicated commit. Then dispatch faion-storybook-agent for stories and faion-frontend-component-agent for typed components. Never merge these into one commit.</statement>
        <rationale>Token promotion is a design decision that deserves its own reviewable commit. Storybook and component generation depend on the promoted tokens; sequencing prevents them from using un-promoted values.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Token promotion and Storybook dispatch sequence">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
# Step 1: promote tokens (human reviews this commit)
promote_tokens(f"designs/variant-{N}-{slug}/tokens.css", "src/styles/globals.css")

# Step 2: Storybook
Task(
    subagent_type="faion-storybook-agent",
    prompt=f"Scaffold Storybook for {project}. Design source: designs/variant-{N}-{slug}/. "
           f"Create stories for every component variant. Wire Chromatic for visual regression."
)

# Step 3: typed components
Task(
    subagent_type="faion-frontend-component-agent",
    prompt=f"Convert designs/variant-{N}-{slug}/ HTML mocks to typed React components "
           f"with cva() variants, cn() merging, and Storybook story files."
)
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent generates 5 variants that share the same Inter font and blue-gray palette.</description>
        <reason>Enforce the diversity constraints explicitly in the prompt. Include a post-generation check: if two variants use the same typeface, regenerate the duplicate before presenting to the user.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent skips a11y audit and delivers variants with contrast failures.</description>
        <reason>Run axe-core per variant during brainstorm, not after selection. Surfacing a variant with WCAG failures wastes selection effort if it must be redesigned.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Refinement agent receives the full brainstorm context and regresses to rejected variants.</description>
        <reason>Pass only the chosen variant's directory and the user feedback. Never include sibling variant files in refinement context.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Variants accumulate in designs/ after PR merge and bloat the repo.</description>
        <reason>Add a designs/ cleanup step in the post-merge PR workflow. Archive or delete rejected variant directories after the chosen direction is merged to main.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/new-variant.sh" purpose="Scaffold a designs/variant-N-slug/ directory with README template."/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-brainstorm.txt" purpose="Full LLM prompt template for generating 3–5 contrastive design variants."/>
    </templates>
  </content>
</methodology>
